         <abstract>
            <p>Stiff systems of ordinary differential equations are characterized by an initial phase in which the solution changes rapidly. Often there is no interest in reproducing this transient phase. A method is proposed for modifying the initial value if the system of differential equations is separably stiff, i.e. is characterized by the occurrence of a few (typically one) large negative real eigenvalues which dominate the others. The modified system does not possess a transient phase, and in the constant coefficient linear case its solution does not differ from that of the original one in the nonstiff components.</p>
          </abstract>
